	  <title>An Example of Turning Systems of Linear Equations into Matrix Equations</title>
	  <caption>Matrix Transposition</caption>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Solve the two systems of linear equations below.</para.body>
         </para>
			
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>
					
\begin{array}{rcrcrcr}
-x &amp; - &amp; y &amp; + &amp; 3z &amp; = &amp; 1 \\
-2x &amp; + &amp; y &amp; - &amp; 3z &amp; = &amp; 4 \\
-x &amp; - &amp; 2y &amp; + &amp; 2z &amp; = &amp; -1
\end{array}\text{ \ and \ }
\begin{array}{rcrcrcr}
-x &amp; - &amp; y &amp; + &amp; 3z &amp; = &amp; 24 \\
-2x &amp; + &amp; y &amp; - &amp; 3z &amp; = &amp; -8 \\
-x &amp; - &amp; 2y &amp; + &amp; 2z &amp; = &amp; -14
\end{array}
					
				</latex>
			      </math.display>
		    </statement.showme>
		
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>First of all we observe that both systems of linear equations have the same coefficient matrix</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
A\ =\
\left[\begin{array}{rrr}
-1 &amp; -1 &amp; 3 \\
-2 &amp;  1 &amp; -3 \\
-1 &amp; -2 &amp; 2
\end{array}
\right]
					
				</latex>
			            </math.display>
			
			            <para>
                  <para.body>This matrix is square-shaped and of size <math>
                        <latex>(3,3)</latex>
                     </math>. If it happens to be invertible, we can use its inverse to conveniently solve both systems. Indeed, we find</para.body>
               </para>
			
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
A^{-1}\ =\
\dfrac{1}{12}\,
\left[\begin{array}{rrr}
-4 &amp; -4 &amp; 0 \\
7  &amp;  1 &amp; -9 \\
5  &amp;  -1 &amp; -3
\end{array}\right]
					
				</latex>
			            </math.display>
			
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Consequently, the first system has the unique solution</para.body>
               </para>
			
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix}\ =\ \dfrac{1}{12}\, 
\left[\begin{array}{rrr}
-4 &amp; -4 &amp; 0 \\
7  &amp;  1 &amp; -9 \\
5  &amp;  -1 &amp; -3
\end{array}\right]
\left[\begin{array}{r} 1 \\ 4 \\ -1 \end{array}\right]\ =\
\dfrac{1}{3}\, \left[\begin{array}{r} -5 \\ 5 \\ 1 \end{array}\right]
					
				</latex>
			            </math.display>
			
			            <para>
                  <para.body>While, the second system has the unique solution</para.body>
               </para>
			
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
\begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{bmatrix}\ =\ \dfrac{1}{12}\, 
\left[\begin{array}{rrr}
-4 &amp; -4 &amp; 0 \\
7  &amp;  1 &amp; -9 \\
5  &amp;  -1 &amp; -3
\end{array}\right]
\left[\begin{array}{r} 24 \\ -8 \\ -14 \end{array}\right]\ =\
\dfrac{1}{6}\, \left[\begin{array}{r} -32 \\ 143 \\ 85  \end{array}\right]
					
				</latex>
			            </math.display>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
